The paper deals with domain adaptation in computer vision, which is a subfield of computer science. The use of CNNs and the evaluation on visual domain benchmarks suggest that the paper belongs to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the use of scatter tensors and the alignment of distributions suggest that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The evaluation on RGB-D and image-to-sketch transfer tasks suggest that the paper may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the use of datasets and evaluation metrics commonly used in information retrieval suggest that the paper may also belong to the information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
